 Record of the Darker Races'', \"Social Uplift\" (page 7), published by the National Association of Colored People (NAACP), May 11, 1911 in New York City.\n</ref>\n|-\n| [[Emmett Chappelle|Chappelle, Emmett]]\n| 1925\u20132019\n| Scientist and researcher\n| Valuable contributions to several fields: medicine, [[biology]], [[food science]], and [[astrochemistry]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Kenneth and Mamie Clark|Clark, Mamie]]\n| 1914\u20132005\n| [[Psychologist]]\n|Conducted 1940s experiments using dolls to study children's attitudes about race\n|\n|-\n| [[Kenneth and Mamie Clark|Clark, Kenneth]]\n| 1917\u20131983\n| [[Psychologist]]\n| First Black president of the American Psychological Association\n|<ref>Bio. True Story, \"Kenneth Bancroft Clark Biography.\" Accessed December 7, 2012. http://www.biography.com/people/kenneth-bancroft-clark-9249475{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>\n|-\n| [[David Crosthwait|Crosthwait, David, Jr.]]\n| 1898\u20131976\n| [[Researcher|Research engineer]]\n| Heating, [[ventilation (architecture)|ventilation]], and [[air conditioning]]; received some 40 US patents relating to [[HVAC]] systems\n|\n|-\n| [[Nick Curtis|Curtis, James H (Nick)]]\n| 1935\u2013\n| Researcher, chemist (electronics/specialty chemicals)\n| Organic ionogen for aluminum electrolytic capacitors, cationic dialdehyde polysaccharides for wet strength paper and others, US Patent Office US Pat #3609467 US Pat #3547423 and others\n|\n|-\n| [[John Dabiri|Dabiri, John]]\n| 1980\u2013\n| [[Biophysicist]]\n| Expert on [[jellyfish]] [[hydrodynamics]] and designer of a vertical-axis [[wind farm]] adapted from [[Shoaling and schooling|schooling fish]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Marie Maynard Daly|Daly, Marie Maynard]]\n| 1921\u20132003\n| [[Chemist]]\n| First black American woman with a PhD in chemistry\n|\n|-\n| [[Mark Dean (computer scientist)|Dean, Mark]]\n| 1957\u2013\n| [[Computer scientist]]\n| Led the team that developed the [[Industry Standard Architect