cestry were not uncovered until 1979, and are still little known today\n|\n|-\n| [[Annie Easley|Easley, Annie]]\n| 1933\u20132011<ref name=\"obits.cleveland.com\">{{cite web|url=http://obits.cleveland.com/obituaries/cleveland/obituary.aspx?n=annie-jean-easley&pid=152269470|title=ANNIE JEAN EASLEY's Obituary on The Plain Dealer|website=The Plain Dealer|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| [[Computer scientist]]\n| Work at the [[Lewis Research Center]] of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] and its predecessor, the [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]]\n|<ref name=\"obits.cleveland.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/oral_histories/NASA_HQ/Herstory/EasleyAJ/AJE_8-21-01.pdf|title=Interview code OHI0026830|website=nasa.gov|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Clarence Ellis (computer scientist)|Ellis, Clarence \"Skip\"]]\n| 1943\u20132014\n| [[Computer scientist]]\n| First African American with a PhD in [[computer science]]; software inventor including OfficeTalk at [[PARC (company)|Xerox PARC]]\n|<ref>[http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/computer-science/ellis_clarencea.html Skip Ellis], Retrieved from Computer Scientists of the African Diaspora web site March 6, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://express.howstuffworks.com/ep-ellis.htm Skip Ellis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025125811/http://express.howstuffworks.com/ep-ellis.htm |date=October 25, 2012 }}, Retrieved from howstuffworks Extraordinary People website, March 6, 2012.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Bisi Ezerioha|Ezerioha, Bisi]]\n| 1972\u2013\n| [[Automotive engineer]]\n| Drag racing engineer and driver\n|\n|-\n| [[Lloyd Noel Ferguson|Ferguson, Lloyd Noel]]\n| 1918\u20132011\n| [[Chemist]], educator\n| Chemistry doctorate, first received (1943, [[University of California, Berkeley]])\n|<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.insightnews.com/news/8333-lloyd-ferguson-a-pioneering-african-american-professorchemist-from-cal-state-la-has-died|newspaper=Insight News|date=Decemb